Last semester, I experienced a situation in which I received feedback that was difficult to hear. I took a class called Women in Entrepreneurship with Kendra Scott, where we were given the option to pitch a business idea. I pitched my idea for an all-in-one shopping platform. After we all pitched our ideas, we were put into teams. I was put into a team where the founder was creating an all-in-one wedding dress website. She then proceeded to take all the fundamental elements of my idea and apply them to her niche.
When I brought up how this bothered me to my professor, she gave me valuable feedback. She suggested that regardless of her taking inspiration from me, I should still stay on the team to learn the feasibility of my idea applied to this niche. At first, I was confused that she didn't understand why it upset me. However, after thinking about it for a few days, I saw the value in her feedback. Regardless of me staying on the team or not, the girl would proceed to use my idea anyway. I realized that I would rather stay and learn from them trying to research and build a minimum viable product from it rather than leave with nothing. Additionally, I cared more about the impact it would make, regardless of it being my idea or not. Therefore, it would be more valuable for me to contribute to the group as well.
From this experience, I learned the importance of taking a step back and assessing the situation before reacting. I was initially upset that someone took my idea, but I learned that it was not about who came up with the idea but rather about the impact the idea could make. I also learned the importance of being open to feedback, even when it is difficult to hear. My professor's feedback allowed me to see the situation in a different light and helped me make a more informed decision.
I am learning to use my voice more and express my power in the most truest to myself possible.

As someone who had previous experience in designing content for my own business’ social media, I felt somewhat disappointed in myself for making this mistake. 

However, I quickly realized that dwelling on my mistake would not benefit me or NAFSN. Instead, I took this as an opportunity to learn and grow. I made a note to be more mindful of the photos I selected in the future, and to always consult with my boss when in doubt. I also recognized the importance of fully understanding the brand and conducting proper research before designing any content. By doing so, I could ensure that my work would always align with NAFSN's values and brand image.

I now approach feedback with a growth mindset, always looking for opportunities to learn and improve my skills.

Last year, my classmates and I were sent a strongly worded email from our principal about our lack of commitment as seniors to the school. She told us that with such attitudes, we should prepare ourselves not to be accepted to the colleges of our choice. 
As ASB Vice President at the time, my president and I held an open forum with our graduating class to brainstorm improvements. Many of the principal's complaints had related to school spirit, cleanliness, and leadership, so we decided to begin there. Before, we'd been telling the underclassmen what to do: clean up after yourselves, participate in class activities, and be respectful to teachers and classmates. However, that wasn't working, so we came up with a leadership-by-example model: we would pick up the school's clutter, hype up events, and be more proactive in classes. It took a couple weeks, but gradually, the younger students also began picking up after themselves and joining in school activities. I learned that change has to be intrinsic, and issues are best resolved with the collective input of the stakeholders.

If I had a million dollars to bring my best idea to life, I would create technology powered by AI  to improve the quality of life for people with disabilities. It could adapt to the person's preferences and can integrate with other smart devices in the home. The app can monitor progress and provide feedback to caregivers and healthcare professionals. I would start by diving into market research. I'd want to make sure my idea was both realistic and had a real impact, so I'd gather as much information as possible. That would mean talking to customers, checking out the competition, and consulting experts in the field. Next up, a project of this magnitude requires a strong team, so I'd assemble a team of designers, engineers, and product managers. Finally I would start work to bring the idea to life. Together, we'd start brainstorming, prototyping, and testing until we had a product that really hit the mark. Of course, this process would take some time, but we would continue working though iterations until we have something we were truly proud of.

Recently, during a project where we created a conversational user interface (CUI), my team received feedback where our professor questioned and commented on how the value of our interface was unclear and lacking. Given the thought our team put into coming up with our idea, we were a bit discouraged to hear how the audience couldn't see the value our CUI brought for users. 

However, when our team re-evaluated our idea, we felt the confusion our audience and professor experienced may have been do to our poor delivery rather than a lacking concept. Thus, for our next critique, we worked to better prepare a presentation that would be intuitive and clear. We worked on creating models that helped visualize how our CUI worked in conjunction with the problem space each feature tackled. We also created a video of our team conducting an experience prototype in order to provide even more visualization of our idea. 

Our team used this opportunity to really think about how our CUI could be more than a "solution" but rather an enhanced experience to a current problem. Our preparations resulted in a complete change in the audience's reaction. Interestingly, from my team's perspective, our idea didn't change too much between the iterations, but to the audience, our CUI went from an unclear and meaningless idea to one that added complexity, provided enjoyment, and inspired curiosity. I think this big jump in how our work was perceived came from our improved method of communicating our vision to the audience. 

We also saw how this impacted the type of responses and feedback we received. During our first critique, the feedback we received told us to take a step backwards and reorganize the foundation of our idea. However, during our second critique, when the audience had a better understanding of our project, we were encouraged with suggestions to help move forward in our CUI.

Background information: violists read alto clef, not treble clef, which is what violinists and pianists read. Simply put, the music notes written on one page for a viola will look different from a page for a violin, even if they’re the same exact notes. 

Imagine this: you try out and make the pit orchestra for your high school musical. Exciting! Except for two things: first, you’re a violist, so there are only two other people in your section (AKA, you really can’t fake playing), and secondly, all the music is in treble clef and you never learned how to play the piano, so you’re kind of screwed because you can’t read the music.

I was stressed out, to say the least. But I lived and breathed treble clef for a solid month, at one point even dreaming about the notes dancing in my sleep. I went from literally writing out the letters on top of each note to being able to play 200 pages of music in time with the orchestra. 

My growth came from hours of practice with my fellow violists, both of whom were just as stressed but also as determined to play beautifully and commit. I just know I wouldn’t have been able to do it without them; a few tears may or may not have been shed together in despair, but we motivated each other and made it through. And I’m really proud that we did, because the end result was absolutely magical. It was four nights of a packed auditorium, high energy all around as we leaped from song to song. Those nights are what made the commitment worth it, but what I’m most proud of is the effort I put into it, despite all the stress-eating and frustration that came out of it.

If I were given a million dollars to build my best idea, I would focus on developing a B2B SaaS platform that revolutionizes how businesses make data-driven decisions. The platform would utilize AI-driven data analytics and insights to provide real-time, actionable recommendations to business leaders.

To bring this idea to life, the first step would be to conduct extensive market research and analysis to identify key pain points and opportunities in the market. This would involve engaging with potential customers and conducting surveys and interviews to gather insights.

Once we have a clear understanding of the market and its needs, the second step would be to build a team of data scientists, AI experts, and software engineers to develop the platform. This team would be responsible for building the algorithms and models that power the data analytics and insights, as well as developing the software that allows customers to access and use the platform.

Finally, the third step would be to roll out the platform to beta customers and begin refining it based on their feedback. This would involve incorporating new features and functionality based on customer needs, as well as continually improving the accuracy and usefulness of the data analytics and insights.

When I was interning for ThatsClutch.com over the summer, I was offered to move from part-time to full-time to assist an employee with plugging information into an Application Tracking System (ATS) spreadsheet. It was a very miserable spreadsheet, over 500 rows long, and color-coded in highlighter yellow, neon green, or bright red. They needed 2 people to do this spreadsheet work because it was very taxing.

I counter-offered my employer and offered to transform their spreadsheet into an automated internal tool for the admin to use. They gladly accepted, excited to see my vision come to reality.

I started by noting all the key functions of the spreadsheet. Then, I moved into user interviews, asking all those at the company who interacted with the spreadsheet how they used it and what purposes it served. Taking this data, I constructed a Figma prototype. I then asked users of the spreadsheet to use this brand-new ATS that followed a Kanban board layout. When one tile was moved into a different column, it automatically sent an email to the applicant so that no human had to do the manual work of sending out templates. I collected feedback, iterated my prototype, and handed it off to the Product Designer to be implemented.

I am happy to say that this cut down the workload for the company by 50%. Instead of having me come on to help another employee with the spreadsheet, only one person could spend a fraction of their original time on the ATS. I was essentially a Product Manager of this ATS at ThatsClutch.com.

As a curriculum development intern at CCE Tompkins last summer, I was tasked with transitioning and adapting a parenting education program into a 2-generation program. My main responsibility was to create a facilitator manual for the program that integrated both the parent/caregiver and youth workshops, one hour for each, with an additional hour for a family session. This was a significant challenge, as the original workshops were two hours each, and it was important to maintain the flow and structure of each session within the limited timeframe.

To tackle this challenge, I researched other parenting program handbooks to identify what activities were being used and how they flowed. I learned that the family portion should be an extension of the previous sessions, which allowed me to extract the most important sections and incorporate new activities where appropriate. I also reached out to parenting educators and professionals to gather suggestions on how to engage participants, caregivers and children respectively, and what examples to include in the workshops.

Throughout the project, I met regularly with my supervisors to ask for feedback and ensure that the components included were of high quality and completeness. By the end of the internship, I successfully compiled the first edition of the manual, and the program committee planned to pilot it this year.

This experience taught me the importance of research, communication, and adaptability in tackling complex projects. I also learned the importance of seeking feedback and continuously improving the project to meet the needs of the participants.

When the COVID-19 pandemic began to rise in March, I reached out to my peers in high school and college and we formed a grassroots nonprofit called Operation Helping Hand. I collaborated with local farms and grocers to divert food from waste and provide steady deliveries of food to families suffering from COVID-induced layoffs and isolation, and I am currently working towards establishing a community “fridge” for the often neglected homeless and underserved in my town. 
As the pandemic continued and the fight for racial justice heightened, I further mobilized the teens within our grassroots to bolster minority turnout in the upcoming election. I developed and facilitated a phone bank and door-to-door campaign reaching 20,000+ minority voters within our town to turn out for local and national candidates. I established a partnership between Operation Helping Hand and the local newspaper to host interviews with local candidates led by my fellow organizers and myself, and in a broader effort, I involved our organizers in national door-to-door efforts through a partnership with Seed the Vote and Generation Rising in order to bolster minority voter turnout within the swing states of Pennsylvania and Arizona. 
Throughout this entire process, I appreciate the opportunities to connect with my peers and help them effectively contribute to the fight for collective liberation of marginalized communities. Having attended 3 Title I schools and experiencing the hurdles of growing up in a first-generation, low-income home, I recognize the systemic roadblocks that continue to limit the BIPOC communities from which I learned and developed, and it is because of these communities I contribute to long-lasting and effective changes to ensure we all thrive.

A year and a half ago, I joined a freshman research initiative; since then, I've been learning all about binge drinking disorders and how to computationally find their genetic roots. A group of 5 other undergraduates and I assessed 530 samples of mice whose genetic brain material was sequenced. From there we were able to identify thousands of genes that could be genetic indicators of alcoholism.
These genes were far too numerous to be easily understood. However, in the past 6 months, I have learned how to computationally categorize all these genes with various tools into about seven biological pathways that are expressed differently in mice that are prone to develop alcohol use disorder. 
As it turns out, many issues in a person’s immune and neural systems that have previously been found to be a result of  binge drinking may also be a cause of binge drinking; thus, alcohol addiction may create a destructive positive feedback loop, wherein high consumption increases the likelihood of even more consumption.

Thankfully, the company extended the deadline to September and we’ve had an opportunity to right our wrongs. Beethoven. This single word is both the title of the course I am currently enrolled in and the first sentence of the novel Beethoven Hero by Scott Burnham. I took this course, which is unrelated to my major, as a way of connecting with my background as a violinist and to explore the background of one of the most recognized composers in history. Although our quarter has just begun, I feel as though I already have so many questions about this topic. What makes Beethoven so great? Those who took up composing after Beethoven always saw him as the pinnacle of music composition and someone to be compared to. Richard Wagner, known as a rising talent at the time, took the role as the supposed heir to the throne and used themes from Beethoven’s famous pieces in his own compositions as a sort of tribute. What did Beethoven do that was different from other composers of his time? Why did many composers see him as both a rival and an obstacle? I find it fascinating how our understanding of Beethoven’s life can help interpret not only his music, but other composers’ music as well. An interesting fact I learned was that there are a number of locks of Beethoven’s hair around the world – Only a handful of which are actually his. The theory that Beethoven died of lead poisoning was actually debunked after DNA testing was done on the lock of hair that had traces of lead, and it was found that the hair belonged to a Jewish woman!

During my first year of college, I worked as a Mandarin teacher at a missionary training center in Provo, Utah. As a part of this job, I taught missionaries fundamental language skills daily in an immersed classroom setting. My manager at the time was incredibly strict, and I would often feel anxiety approaching the days when she would come in to audit my class. 

Once I was doing a teaching demonstration during an audit, and I handled a teaching situation poorly, leaving the missionaries feeling confused and discouraged. Immediately after the demonstration, my manager pulled me aside and let me know exactly what I did wrong, telling me that my demonstration was hard to follow and ineffective. It hurt to hear this feedback as I had spent a lot of time preparing this demonstration. However, I thanked my manager for the feedback and planned to do better the next time. 

The following week, I reported to my manager my goal and plans to do better in my upcoming demonstration, and I asked if I could report to her on my progress. She agreed, and for the next few months, I made this weakness of mine a focus point. During this experience, I saw major improvement in my teaching demonstrations and learned several valuable lessons. 

First, admitting imperfection and being willing to learn from mistakes is the best way to handle constructive criticism. Second, setting goals and plans are critical for measuring growth. Ever since this experience, I have made a consistent effort to embrace direct feedback and see it with a more positive lens.

Although I was initially deflated by the CEO's remarks, my team and I took the time to revise our presentations and conduct more research and surveys to better meet the CEO's demands. By helping to build a reliable, easy-to-use product, I can use my skills to make a positive impact in the world while staying connected to my community.

I have taken on many roles in tech: UI/UX Intern, UX Researcher, Product Development Analyst, and Engineer. As a Product Manager, I can bridge my skills from each of these experiences to guide the lifecycle of a product.

2023 - As part of a class, my partner and I are creating a Figma prototype for an Instacart competitor app. By using Human-Computer Interaction methods (Pareto analysis, Error analysis, Flow analysis, Usability testing, Cognitive walkthrough, Prototyping, and many more), we are designing the ideal platform for professional shoppers.

2022 Fall - I was promoted from intern to Product Development Analyst at ThatsClutch.com. I conducted UX Research for dashboard setup, profile editing, and other user tasks on the website. 

2022 Summer - As a UI/UX Intern at ThatsClutch.com, I assisted in UX Research, Figma prototyping, and streamlining internal processes. My biggest achievement at this internship was converting their ATS spreadsheet into an internal tool for the admin. This involved stakeholder interviews, user interviews, prototyping, usability testing, iterating, and presenting my final solution to the team.

2021 - I led my team through the 5-step human-centered design process to create a Figma prototype for a financial literacy app geared toward college students. The project was continued into 2022 when a partner and I delivered an in-person financial literacy workshop to over 20 attendees.

2020 - I worked on a team of Mechanical Engineers to prototype, construct, and test a “sensory pod” for the Houston Museum of Natural Sciences. Patrons of the museum can get overwhelmed with sights, sounds, and smells and need to retreat to a dedicated space to decompress. This is especially true for children with Autism Spectrum Disorder or ADHD. I conducted user interviews, did problem space research, created scaled prototypes, and then physically constructed a large room with my team. All the while, we had to write Engineering Memos and present them to our stakeholders.

I have always prided myself on being a strong writer, but in my first World Literature class in college, I got back my first essay graded with red mark after red mark. She told me I had a problem with rambling, and that I needed to work on organization in my writing. This was difficult to hear because I always considered myself a very organized person and I thought my attention to detail and lengthy explanations was what made my writing strong. It felt like criticism coming out of the blue because no teacher had given me proper feedback on my writing before. I took her suggestions to heart and visited her in office hours, implementing a pre-writing structure she recommended. In my next essay, I was careful to employ the strategies I had learned in my class and make a conscious effort to evaluate my work at every step. I ended up doing far better on the second essay, but the more valuable lesson was realizing how to relearn skills I thought I knew and how to develop adaptability in anything I do. Self-evaluation is crucial in any career or industry, and learning early on in college how to  grow from criticism was a valuable tool to have.

The hardest thing I've ever done was train for my dance Arangetram. An Arangetram is the  debut solo performance of the Indian classical dance style, Bharatanatyam, where a dancer ascends the stage after years of learning and training. An Arangetram is typically a 3-4 hour long performance that takes incredible physical and mental endurance. I had been learning dance for 13 years prior, but really began training a year before my Arangetram. In addition to building up stamina, strength, and stability, I had to manage many details surrounding the logistics of the event, from organizing musicians, booking a venue, and managing seating. As a senior in high school at the time, I was also dealing with considerable academic stress. It was challenging to balance all these things at once, but it taught me very valuable lessons about time management and prioritization. Training for my Arangetram took immense amounts of discipline, because it was such a long-term project with little to no strict "deadlines" to meet until the final performance. I learned how to keep myself on track to meet my goals and how to not lose sight of the goal itself.  I also learned how to delegate tasks and manage a team -- after trying to balance all the logistics myself, I realized it was more efficient to assign tasks to my friends and family, who were all eager to help. In the end, I was able to execute a performance I was proud of, especially given the challenges I faced in the journey leading up to it.

During my sophomore year, I went through sorority recruitment, a challenging process that resulted in receiving some difficult feedback. The process involves evaluating potential new members based on their personalities and appearance, and making hugs cuts without having to give a reason, and it's easy to feel like something is wrong with you. During one of my recruitment interviews, however, the girl interviewing me shared her experience and advised me not to take it personally. She explained that it's all part of the process, and sometimes a person just doesn't fit what the house is looking for. Initially, it was tough not to take the feedback personally, as the interviewer knew very little about me beyond my appearance and small talk. However, I am an extremely organized individual who likes to document everything. So, as I went through recruitment, I kept notes in a small book about my feelings after each house, what they stood for, who I talked to, and more. By doing this, I was able to understand each sorority's unique "personality” and “culture"  and eventually found a house where I felt I belonged. This house provided me with lifelong friends, and the experience taught me to be more confident in myself by emphasizing my strengths and unique qualities. By being authentic, I found a house with like-minded people that made my experience enjoyable, instead of trying to fit into a mold that would have led me to a house that wasn’t right for me. I learned that I should stay true to myself, trust the process, receive  feedback constructively and view failure as an opportunity to learn and grow. Also that there is always something to learn from failure, and reflecting on this set me up for success in the long-run. This lesson has translated closely into my attitude towards internship applications - just because one opportunity does not work out, it does not mean that I am not skilled or valued, it just means that I have to keep looking and learning from my experiences, and the right opportunity will come along.

Last year, after attending a 12-week course on computational biology, I applied for a paid summer research fellowship under the same professor; unfortunately, I was denied the position. After seeking feedback from the program director, she told me that despite my strong efforts during the class, she felt that I lacked previous knowledge with programming languages relative to other candidates. Ultimately, my personal growth throughout the 12-week course was not sufficient to offset the pre-existing knowledge gap.
This was very difficult feedback to hear, as I had put a lot of effort and time into my application and had hoped to gain valuable research experience over the summer. However, I didn't let this rejection stop me from pursuing my goals.
Instead, I decided to volunteer at the same research lab that summer, hoping to enhance my technical skill set, which was the main point of weakness addressed in our feedback session. It was a tough decision to volunteer, as it meant giving up my summer job to work for free, but I was determined to learn and grow.
As it turned out, volunteering was the best decision I could have made. Not only did I learn much more than I would have in the paid position, but I was also able to develop relationships with the researchers and gain valuable insights into the world of academic research. In fact, later that semester, I was accepted to serve as an academic mentor for new students in the research lab. 
This experience taught me that sometimes, the best way to grow is to take a risk and step out of your comfort zone. While receiving difficult feedback can be discouraging, it's important to keep pushing forward and seeking out opportunities to learn and improve. In the end, my persistence and willingness to learn helped me gain valuable experience and become a leader in the research community.

To have a million dollars, many major issues in this world could be supported and addressed. One of my personal interests and areas I would like to work toward in the future is children's education. Education is an important value of mine, and looking at the different education systems around the world, we can see the stark contrast between systems that are more developed than others. One area that I would like to use a large fund is to bridge this gap by creating more educational opportunities for marginalized communities. An idea to implement this is to develop a software program that is not only an educational tool but a platform for students to make connections and build their experience.

With a large fund, I think the first step to approaching this step would be hiring knowledgable educators to help build useful learning resources. This could range from tutoring videos to practice activities to even live question/answer sessions. These resources would create value by giving free access to a variety of tools based on a student's needs. A main goal of this idea would be for low-income students to have comparable educational experiences as the average student. Providing access to resources, counseling, and tutoring would allow them to have this extra boost that other students have.

Currently, programs that provide free educational tools exist, but this idea can expand a student's opportunities to also give them a place to connect with other students and educators. Students could find opportunities to build relationships that encourage their academic progress. They could have mentors to guide them, and I envision this would be helpful for high school students wanting to explore experiences in different domains. The program would not be limited to experiences on a screen but creating social connections as well.

A final feature of this program could be creating a dashboard for students to organize their personal academic goals and achievements. The software could lead students to other resources based on their goals. This could start a student's pathway to careers and broaden their opportunities outside of their community as well. 

It would be instrumental to create a single software that meets various needs of a student. The average student is able to access these tools and experiences with little difficulty, but in marginalized communities, there is not only a lack of resources but more importantly, opportunities. This idea would be providing these students with information and technology to build their academia with quality resources.

In July 2022, I heard the following words: “it will take one year for you to recover”. My brain couldn’t compute. Over the next two weeks, I had to keep reminding myself - I tore my ACL, and it will be a yearlong recovery. 12 months. This was an injury that even professional athletes sometimes didn’t recover from, how would I? I spent that summer and fall unable to walk properly, mostly confined to my house. It was as if I was living through the height of the covid pandemic again! As a previously athletic person, the mental toll of losing my main source of meditation and social outlet was unlike anything I had ever dealt with before. Framing small things, such as the first time I was able to walk without crutches to my neighborhood ice cream store with a friend, into memorable and positive experiences helped get me through.  
I am currently in the middle of my recovery, working with a physical therapist to strengthen my quad muscles and get back to doing the things I love - hoping I can get back to running this summer. One of the positives that came out of this ordeal was that I found a love for weightlifting. I tried to get into it over the years, but usually gave up. This time though, since it was the only form of exercise I could participate in, I dove in deep and began amassing proper knowledge regarding anatomy, muscle building, nutrition, etc. I have been working out consistently every week since last September and know that it will be a habit in my life for years to come.

A result I'm most proud of would be creating a mobile service for a toy company. For many design projects, I struggled feeling whether my skills were adequate enough because I lacked a background in visual design. However, as I worked on more projects and became more exposed to design techniques, I felt myself becoming more comfortable and creative with design. I think this project was meaningful for me because it was a project I felt very involved in and passionate about. From brainstorming to  making design choices, I felt the ideas and concepts I had to offer helped make some important decisions. 

I think this project was also one I felt the most passionate about. Our team was challenged to think about creating a mobile service in a different way. Melissa & Doug emphasizes creating toys to enhance children’s play in a screen-free environment, but creating a service that shifts the focus to a screen would undermine their goals. Our team thought of possible ways we could still create a mobile service without taking away the creative and engaging experience of playing with toys. Our team decided to create a service that could emphasize these memories of play through a time capsule service that logs the journey of a toy. Children would still have their full childhood experience in a screen-free zone, and parents would be able to log their children’s favorite memories, which could be replayed when the children are older. The goals of our service were to create a sense of nostalgia and source of keeping core childhood memories. 

Having a background working with children, I think I felt passionate about letting kids be kids. Nowadays so many kids are tied to a screen, and many times, it's done in an unhealthy way. I feel strongly about letting kids build social and healthy experiences that allow them to exercise their minds, grow their curiosity, and enhance their creativity.

In our first semester here at Cornell, one of the biggest struggles my friends and I had was figuring out how to get home. For many of us, the commute consists of a series of buses, trains and planes – it’s pretty overwhelming to sift through all the options and you can never be quite sure that you’re getting the best fit for your needs. 
To address that, I thought of a web-app idea in which a student can type in a location and find a list of transportation options, something like an Expedia, but for every leg of a trip. The app will then retrieve and display data, like bus fare or plane price for a specific time. The user can filter by mode or price to find the best ride for their needs. 
The need for a product like this expands far past the Cornell campus that it was originally brainstormed for – anyone that travels using public and private transportation would benefit from it. 
Before bringing this vision to life, I would first conduct user research to quantify the need for the app. This would span people from all walks of life and also from a geographically diverse pool. Once I’ve ascertained the market for the product and what features the users would like to see in the app, I would gather a small team of developers, designers and a PM that are hopefully as passionate about the product as I am. Then we would create a minimum viable product before beta testing with a small group of users. Over time, the product will only become more sophisticated, and hopefully the consumer base will continue to grow as well.

If I had a million dollars to bring my best idea to life, it would be a revolutionary healthcare platform that could detect diseases, injuries, and illnesses through a smartphone. Healthcare costs are skyrocketing due to the high demand and limited supply of medical professionals. To tackle this global issue, I propose developing a platform that uses cutting-edge generative AI technology to diagnose patients.

Here's how it works: patients will describe their symptoms to a chatbot, which will use sophisticated algorithms to filter out medical conditions that don't fit the presented symptoms. Next, the patient will use their smartphone camera to take a picture of the affected area. The platform will then use object recognition technology to compare the image to a database of similar cases and provide the best possible match.

Finally, the platform will provide the patient with a detailed recovery plan, including recommended treatments and medications, as well as follow-up instructions. This approach would revolutionize healthcare delivery by making diagnosis and treatment accessible to people regardless of their location or financial circumstances.

With this platform, patients could receive an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment without having to visit a doctor's office. This would greatly reduce healthcare costs and make healthcare more accessible to people in remote areas or those with limited mobility. Overall, I believe that this platform has the potential to transform the way we think about healthcare and revolutionize medical diagnosis and treatment.

I was that with a fast approaching deadline, my group's speech had to be scrapped and rewritten. My initial response was between feeling defeated and frustrated. However as I began to rework the speech, I saw that this decision was in fact crucial for a successful speech. This turned my response from frustration to being grateful. I learned that sometimes we can be blind to the flaws in our creation. Not only is receiving a second opinion necessary for review, but to point out and bring a perspective you may not originally see. I also learned no matter how much we want something to be successful in one try that will unlikely be the case. This experience also taught me how to revise my work and learn to accept criticism.

After reading about Pinwheel's story, I was immediately impressed by Pinwheel's mission to provide children and teens with a safer mobile environment. As the oldest in a large family, I have repeatedly seen my younger siblings be affected adversely by technology usage, leading them to feel increased anxiety, a lack of desire to interact with others, and difficulty pulling away from a screen. 

Seeing technology directly affect my younger siblings has made me realize the scope and severity of technology addiction among children. As this problem is at the core of Pinwheel's products and mission, I have a strong desire to be part of Pinwheel and work towards a viable solution--not just for my family, but for other families, too. Therefore, I am incredibly interested on working at Pinwheel and contributing my own experience and ideas towards building the company.

Recently, I have been learning a lot about the responsibilities of a product manager in my current position as Vice President of Finances in the BYU Product Society. In this position, I oversee the club finances and help coordinate the event logistics and the speaker selection for our weekly meetings. This experience has taught a lot about what to expect as a product manager, including how to succeed in interviews, network with different PMs, and build a strong resume. In addition, this experience has given me opportunities to practice leadership, public speaking, and financial management skills.

When constructing the "sensory pod", we had to attach wheels to the bottom of the room so that it was mobile. At the very beginning of our project, we were given size constraints for the pod. It turned out that the pod was half an inch too tall, but we had already attached our wheels. If we were to keep the pod as is, our design would not have fit into the museum's elevators. We were able to rectify the situation by finding new wheels on a very tight budget. 

Additionally, the same project had a sliding-door mechanism similar to a drawer. Unfortunately, the sliding doors had large welts, which made it hard to expand and decompress the pod without them getting caught on our already-problematic wheels. At this point, our semester was over and we had to face the fact that the next team would be handling this new problem with the pod.

My research focused on using a geographic information system (GIS) and satellite imagery to create predictive maps pointing to potential areas of spotted lanternfly infestation in vineyards. I also became a research assistant at Drexel University for an undergrad/grad spotted lanternfly project that created a machine learning application to remotely detect the insects’ egg masses using drones. I would develop a city-wide parking platform and app that allows Austin residents to asses parking availability within a certain mile radius from the convenience of their phones. Parking in Austin is a huge problem -- it can both be inaccessible, time-consuming, and expensive. With this app, drivers could filter for location, price, and other features (covered vs street) to allow them to more efficiently park, eliminating unnecessary vehicle circling and idling. To implement this, first I would conduct a survey of Austin residents to see whether an app like this would be used and if there is a market for it. Next, I would build a team of software engineers and designers with technical expertise combined with business strategists (especially those with experience in transportation and city planning) that can implement logistical solutions. Finally, I would test the app on a small sample of residents -- just UT students perhaps-- to assess its success and make changes as needed before launching it on a larger scale.

During a family trip to New Zealand last summer, I was faced with the hardest thing I've ever done: convincing my 16-year-old brother that cliff jumping was a dangerous idea. As an individual who values careful planning and calculated risks, I was hesitant to embrace my brother's spontaneity. When my brother first suggested cliff jumping, my initial reaction was to dismiss it as too risky. I knew that cliff jumping could be dangerous, especially if you are not experienced or familiar with the area. However, my brother was persistent and convinced that it would be a thrilling experience. I decided to take a more assertive approach and proposed that we look into safer options. After researching different activities, we came across skydiving, which was surprisingly not only safer but also more regulated in New Zealand. I presented this alternative to my brother and explained why it was a better option. Through teamwork and thorough research, we were able to make an informed decision that ultimately led to a once-in-a-lifetime experience of jumping 15,000 feet from a plane - no big deal compared to arguing with a 16 year old boy, right? And while the experience was undoubtedly exhilarating, it taught me an important lesson about embracing uncertainty and taking risks in a responsible and informed manner. By leveraging my ability to analyze and synthesize information, and my willingness to take calculated risks, I am confident in my ability to make sound decisions in any situation. Ultimately, this experience reinforced my belief that teamwork, careful planning, and a willingness to embrace uncertainty can lead to great rewards. Also, there isn't much 16 year old boys are afraid of.

If I were given a million dollars to build my best idea, I would focus on developing a mobile app that connects small business owners with affordable marketing solutions. I believe that small businesses are the backbone of our economy, and they often struggle with marketing and advertising due to limited budgets.
First, I would conduct market research to identify the most pressing marketing challenges facing small business owners. I would also reach out to business owners directly to get feedback on the concept and gather input on their specific needs.
Second, I would create a detailed plan for execution. This would include building a team of experienced marketers and developers to help build and market the app, developing a user-friendly interface, and partnering with affordable marketing services providers to offer exclusive deals to app users.
Third, I would execute the plan and track progress closely. This would include beta testing the app, launching it to the public, and gathering feedback to make ongoing improvements. I would also focus on building a strong community of users and leveraging social media and other marketing channels to drive user growth.
Overall, my goal would be to create a sustainable business that not only helps small business owners succeed but also has a positive impact on the broader economy. I believe that with the right approach and a focus on solving a real-world problem, this idea has the potential to make a significant impact.

At the current moment, the best idea I have is for an app that allows people to sign up and attend dates anonymously as a “third wheel”. The main purpose of this app comes from the common situation where couples will go on a date together but have no one to nice photos for them without hiring an expensive private photographer. And while they could always ask people around them, no one wants to be that person who asks a stranger to keep retaking the photo until they like it (“Does this photo look ok?” “Yes, of course! Thanks!” <-- usually said without even looking at the picture taken). As the number of the same repackaged dating apps increase, I want to introduce this idea as a fresh accompaniment. 

With a million dollars to jumpstart this idea, the first thing I would do is hire a team. Although I may have an idea in its early stages, in order to see this product through to the end, I believe I need a team that I can trust and rely on. Whether through an application process or asking around my friends, I will build a balanced team that isn’t just computer science heavy, but with foundations in a breadth of fields. For this stage of my project, my motto will be “I hope I’m not the smartest person in this room”. 

Once I have a team that I am satisfied with, I will begin the development stages of my project. I hope to follow a structure that is rigid enough where it is organized, but flexible enough where my team will have room to improvise and try things out. In terms of the actual development, first we will host weekly meetings in which each member goes over what they are planning to do and what they have accomplished already. We will go over and analyze any current issues or potential obstacles to the product. Then, we will rework our structure for the app to accommodate these changes. Once we have gone through this cycle a number of times, hopefully within around 6 months, we will have a prototype that is usable and functions without any severe bugs. An important feature of my app I would like to implement during this phase is how couples are matched with their “third wheel”. My vision for the interface is that couples pay a membership fee to join the app, and they will then release their event listing with the date, time, and specific needs. There will be a base price to hire a “third wheel” priced by the hour, which covers simple tasks like taking candid photos during the duration of the date and taking photos when asked to. There will also be an option for more unique dates to accommodate for couples who may just need another body for reservations to restaurants or attractions, as some only take reservations for parties of 3 or more. The third wheel can then give a like for the events they are interested in, and be matched with a couple that accepts them. The incentive for the third wheel is to get paid (The hourly base wage + some amount of money from our seed funding, which will eventually turn into money from the membership fees) or go to events they may not normally get to go to (Free meal at restaurants that the couple and company splits, participation in escape rooms or tours, etc.).  

Third, with all the remaining money, I would buy as many eco-friendly tricycles as possible and donate them to local schools in the area. Because who doesn’t need a third wheel :)

During a UX project for a class last semester, my team and I were all beginners with no prior experience in the field. While working on one of our assignments, I noticed that we were not following the instructions that our professor had introduced in class. However, I didn't bring it up to the team because I thought it might not be a big deal. Unfortunately, our grade suffered as a result. We were all upset, and when I told my team that the professor actually taught that in class, one of my group members criticized me for not speaking up earlier.

Feeling frustrated and wronged, I initially wanted to defend myself and blamed my team members for not paying attention in class. However, I soon realized that this was not the right attitude to have. I took a step back, took a deep breath, and tried to see the situation from their perspective. I acknowledged that, while I had known the information, I had not effectively communicated it to the group. I realized that I needed to be more proactive in communicating my concerns and in ensuring that everyone was on the same page.

With this realization, I expressed to my team that I would make an effort to be more vocal in the future and encouraged us to work together more effectively. 

From this experience, I learned that it is crucial to voice my concerns and to communicate effectively within a team. Nothing is too small to bring up, especially when I have concerns or doubts. It's important to be an active participant and to ensure that everyone is working towards the same goals. By doing so, I was able to turn this difficult feedback into a valuable learning experience that has helped me to become a better team player.

I visited my grandparents in India during the pandemic and that's when I dined in at Darshinis - a chain of local eateries in Bengaluru, served by dedicated staff-members who often do 18-hour shifts just to support their families. It is here that I met Madesh. 

One evening, I noticed Madesh looking slightly distraught and he shared his grief of being unable to afford education for his son, Manju. For me, learning his reality was heartbreaking. I took a moment to reassure him and decided to do everything in my power to help as I believe in the promise of opportunity that education opens for all.

I researched for schools that offered education to underprivileged children. This led me to ‘Bridge-School’, which provides free education to the needy. I was happy to share with Madesh that Manju could secure admission at the school. The look on his face was priceless as this education will offer Manju upward mobility in life. Later, I realized there are 100s who can’t afford basic education in my grandparents’ vicinity.

I created awareness about this school and further helped many such children get access to free schooling and decided to volunteer with ‘Bridge-School’ myself, where I taught Mathematics and English. I continue to pursue this endeavor at the ‘Shiv Nadar Foundation’, once my grandparents relocated to Delhi. Through the pandemic, we crowdfunded to arrange tablets for children so they could continue their education online.

One of my goals will always be to develop an enlightened future for the underprivileged, where they can get fair opportunities to turn fearless dreams into reality!

At the start of this school year, I volunteered at a stadium concessions stand during the first UT football game of the 2022 season. The game had over 100,000 attendees, and our volunteer crew (which had only half the recommended number of staff due to a staffing shortage) lacked any prior experience in cooking the foods.
The sheer volume of people was overwhelming, and the pressure to keep up with demand was intense. I was constantly on my feet, trying to prepare food quickly and efficiently while also ensuring that everything was cooked properly and up to standard.
In addition, the fact that there were only 7 other volunteers, rather than the recommended 15, made it challenging to manage the workload and maintain a high level of customer service. It was a test of my organizational skills, as I had to prioritize tasks and ensure that everything was running smoothly despite the challenges. We ended up running only 5 registers rather than 8 because it was much easier to have 3 dedicated "runners" fulfilling orders instead of each cashier getting their own order.
Ultimately, despite all the difficulties, I learned a lot from the experience. I learned the importance of staying calm under pressure and being adaptable in unexpected situations. I also learned the value of teamwork and communication, as we all had to work together to keep things running smoothly.

As a UX designer for my team at Texas Convergent, I received difficult feedback during a project. Our original  goal was to build an online thrift store for college students, and we had made good progress on feature prioritization and Figma wireframes. However, one of the organization's leads pointed out an existing product that already addressed the problem we were trying to solve. Hearing this feedback was frustrating because it felt like our work was for nothing, would set us behind schedule, and we would have to redo our feature prioritization, mockups, and user research. But after discussing with the team, I took a positive outlook and suggested we could pivot our idea to solve a similar need. We came up with a renting platform for college students for clothes. This experience taught me to always do proper research and not become demotivated by setbacks. Moreover, I also became aware of the negative impact sunk cost biases can have on a team’s success. Our persistence paid off, as our presence in the project helped us win the best demo day presentation out of the 15 competing teams.

I once received feedback from a team member in a group project that my communication style was too direct and was perceived as confrontational. That was never my intention as I just like to work in a very detailed manner. Although I felt misunderstood, I realized that I could adjust the way I spoke to my group members and spoke in a more collaborative and empathetic manner leading to a successful project.

When working on the first sprint for GameFlo, our team was tasked with creating a digital tutorial. This was my first professional task with specific guidelines. My inexperience with working with a group was evident, as the group broke into multiple separate groups to split up the project. The manager took notice due to inconsistencies in our work. He informed us that if we didn't make changes to our work methods, we would be dropped from our project. This feedback was difficult to listen to, as I always saw myself as a good group worker. However, I didn't realize that I was ostracising parts of the group by splitting up the workload, affecting our work. In the meetings after that, we actively worked better to improve our group work. We each took the feedback personally, making sure all of our opinions were heard. This feedback improved my group work, which is a valuable skill to have as a product manager.

1. Create an MVP.

The average person produces 7 metric tonnes of CO2 in a year. However, during 2021 alone, Taylor Swift’s private jet produced over 8,000 tonnes. (Sorry, Swifties!)
If I were given a million dollars, I would develop a carbon emission reduction program specifically for private jet travel.
First, I would conduct research and user interviews with celebrities and other private jet owners to find the main issues they encounter that are adding to their carbon emissions generated by their flights. This program would need to be tailored specifically to the unique needs and habits of private jet travel. I believe the best way to do this would be to reduce the number of airport changes empty planes are forced to make due to storage issues, and use these air crafts as cargo transportation when they are forced to be moved without passengers.
Second, I would develop a platform on which these solutions would be implemented. This would include creating a backend to identify where planes are, which planes are incoming,  and which planes are departing each airport. There would also need to be a user interface for both cargo based companies, and the private jet owners to interact with.
Third, I would work to establish partnerships with private jet charter companies and other stakeholders in the industry to encourage their participation in the program. This would involve educating them about the importance of carbon emission reduction and the potential benefits of participating in our program. This would also involve leveraging social media, targeted advertising, and other channels to reach a wide audience of potential participants.
Ultimately, my goal would be to create a self-sustaining program that could significantly reduce the environmental impact of private jet travel while still allowing celebrities and other private jet owners to enjoy the convenience and flexibility of this mode of transportation.

My fraternity holds Executive Board meetings every Sunday for two hours. During the meetings, we discuss our ongoing projects and troubleshoot any issues that have arisen. There's bound to be disagreement in a room full of 12 young adults from various backgrounds, but it's typically quite civil. 
A few months ago, our President pulled me aside. He wanted to talk to me about how I carried myself during these meetings, telling me that although my opinions were often correct, I wasn't phrasing them correctly. At that time, I was very much a "let the facts speak for themselves" type of person and would approach these meetings from a viewpoint of logos rather than pathos. He told me that when dealing with the perspectives of others, people want to see how it relates more to them and their values. By coming out of the gate so focused on details, I wasn't selling my opinion properly to the rest of the board. 
Initially, I was taken aback but thankful that he shared that with me.  After thinking about it, I realized just how correct he was. Over the past few months, I've been making a conscious effort to change how I present information, purposefully thinking about who my audience is and how I can best relate my ideas to them. As a result, I've felt much more persuasive and present in meetings, not only in my fraternity but in the other organizations I participate in as well. I learned how to handle myself better and how valuable it is to surround yourself with people who are comfortable criticizing you. Without him giving me advice, I wouldn't have improved as a leader so suddenly.

After getting negative feedback to this, I was disspointed in that I had failed this task but decided to take accountability and set up a meeting with the project manager about it. During this meeting, I admitted to my mistakes and asked detailed questions on how I can improve the backlog. After doing this, I spent a couple extra hours at work that day fixing the log. From this situation, I learned that everyone makes mistakes but it's what you do after that matters more. This includes taking accountability, asking detailed questions, and making sure that the mistake is not repeated.

Currently, I am the PR Head for the TEDxCMU organization, an organization that helps organize the ted talks on campus by inviting speakers all over the world. Last year, for our main event, we had one of our six invited speakers drop out 2 weeks before the event. This was stressful for me because I knew that many of our audience members were coming for this specific speaker.  As PR head, I had to find a way to mitigate while still being courteous of members who may not want to attend anymore. Therefore, I took the time to check in with our dropped out speaker to understand if this was something we can work around. Unfortunately, this was not something that I could have helped them with. Therefore, I decided to reach out to other speakers who had interviewed, asking if they would still be interested in speaking in front of an audience. I offered a gift card to compensate for the inconvenience and unfortunate circumstances. Sadly, none of these speakers were available. Therefore, I began to reach out to CMU and Pittsburgh clubs who focused on the same topic as our dropped out speaker. Luckily, a student was excited to give a talk, and we were able to secure our speaker. Once I posted the announcement, I found that less people than I expected asked for refunds as we were able to secure another speaker with a similar talk. However, I still was able to give a refund to those who did not want to come anymore, and also a goodie bag to maintain that goodwill between our organization and the general public. As a result, we were able to salvage the event that we worked so hard to put on and it was extremely successful with more than 500 attendees.

My interest in product came about when I began as a project management intern for a non-profit called Generation She. I discussed with the CEO the resources we could provide women to break into tech, and we created software that matches the women in the GenShe network to top startups while creating a network of women who uplift each other. Working on a product from start to finish, from ideation to beta launching, gave me the perspective that the PM who is handling the product not only handles the process but also the nuance of how the product is positioned in the world. I found myself excited by the notion that each product can have my perspective woven into it and I realized the importance of guiding myself into the right headspace to ensure that the product is streamlined for success and impact. With this notion, I became a product manager for many different spaces, including my own startup, On The Table, TEDxCornellUniversity’s development team, and even my pro-bono consulting engagements. For both On The Table and my client in the engagement, we work with food and beverage products. However, even if the end goal is not a digital product, the process from start to finish looks incredibly similar. With my knowledge of ideating and iterating, I’ve been able to improve the product and experience of both OTT and my client’s business. Using a PM’s perspective as standard practice in my team has helped us be the consumer while also being the creator, helping us work hand-in-hand with our community to deliver better products and have more impact. To dig deeper, there were even teams like TEDxCornellUniversity that did not have a product manager. There was a design team and an engineering team, but they were misaligned, leading to miscommunication and even big disagreements that would set our entire team back by months. I used my skills of delegating tasks, managing people, and overall striking a delicate balance between engineers and designers to get the website finished in 3 weeks, when it had taken so long to  even get started. I think the manner and practices of a PM can greatly affect the product, team environment, and mission which is why I want to be a PM so, I can use my unique background to create better products and better impact.

Social Economics has been a really fascinating field that I've found myself reading more about. Many people are familiar with the subject through Game Theory (i.e. Prisoner's Dilemma, etc.), but the subject has much more substance than that. It's primarily about how we, as individuals or groups, operate outside of market incentives. It can best be thought of as "what we do when there isn't a supply and demand curve?". 
As someone who loves philosophy, I feel this subject really gets at the core of why we make the decisions we do. Economics, to me, isn't primarily a study of markets, but rather how we view choice. While that's often applied to business decision-making when experiencing various market forces, I do really appreciate the nuance found in the microlens of the individual.
